Understanding of problem domain:¶

To analyze and comprehend Balck Friday Sales data to predict the purchase in Retail Sector and applying supervised machine learning algorithms: Logistic regression, Naive Bayes,KNeighborsClassifier,Random Forest. Here we analyse different features like gender ,age,stay in current city,product category,marital status how this impact on purchase behaviour and how we improve the purchase.

Pre-Processing..¶

Machine learning can not process categorical columns for process so we have to convert each categorical column to numerical column. there are many way to convert categorical column to numerical column here we use label encoding which is module of sklearn modul.¶

In [70]:
## pre-prosses lable encoding.
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
columns_to_encode = ['Gender','Age','City_Category','Stay_In_Current_City_Years','purchase_category']
le = LabelEncoder()
for col in columns_to_encode:
    df[col] = le.fit_transform(df[col])

Splitting DataSet to Training and Testing [Ratio 70:30] which means 70% data to training and 30% data to testing.¶

In [72]:
## spliting data into training and testing.
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
# Features and target variable
X = df.drop(['purchase_category','User_ID','Product_ID','purchase_group','purchase_category'], axis=1)  # Replace 'target_column' with your actual target column name
y = df['purchase_category']
# Split data into training and testing sets
x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.3,random_state=42) #test-size=20% #random-state shuffel data to avoid biasness

Model Application [4 Models]¶

Summary About Models:¶

Model 1 : Logistic regression is chose for simplicity it's easy to interpretant and widely used it easily classifies unknown records and convert there probability to 0 and 1¶

Model 2: Naive Bayes algorithm chose for it's high dimentional process and speed it processes easy with high dimentional data¶

Model 3: k-Nearest Neighbors model chose because versatile nature it's a non parametric model which capture complex decision boundries based on the data structure¶

Model 4: Random Forest chose for high accuracy is a powerful tree based algorithm which create number of trees during training phase this algorithm reduce risk of overfitting and improve overall prediction random forest is a part of ensemble learning it creat multiple models and combines them to slove problem it give easy prediction and improve overall accuracy.¶

[1] Logistic Regression..¶

In [76]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# Logistic Regression Classifier
model = LogisticRegression(random_state=100, solver='liblinear', max_iter=2000)  # Increase max_iter if needed
model.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Predict using Logistic Regression 
pred = model.predict(x_test)

# Evaluate Logistic Regression
log_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, pred)
print("Logistic Regression accuracy is %2.2f" % log_accuracy)
print("Logistic Regression Classifier Report:\n", classification_report(y_test,pred))

After pre-processing split the data into training and testing. Apply machine learning model here first model which we applied is logistic regression.

Accuracy is logistic regression is 88% we also print classification report which include accuracy, precision, recall, f1-score Accuracy: matric to analyse classification model in machine learning. Number of correct predictions/ total predictions. Formula: TN+TP/TN+FP+TP+FN

Precision: ratio of correctly predict positive samples from total positive predict. Formula: TP/TP+FP

Recall: ratio of correctly positive prediction from all samples from actual sample. Formula: TP/TP+FN

F1 score: harmonic mean of the precision and recall of classification model. F1score=2 * recall * precision/recall + precision.

This all calculation calculated from ratio of true positive, true negative, false positive, false negative

True positive [TP]: actual value is true model also predict it true its true positive. True negative [TN]: actual value is false model predict it false its true negative. False positive [FP]: actual value is true model predict it true its false positive. False negative [FN]: actual value is false model predict it true its false negative.

[2] Naive Bayes.¶

In [82]:
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# Assuming x_train, y_train, x_test, and y_test are already defined

# Naive Bayes Classifier
nb = GaussianNB()
nb.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Predict the test data using Naive Bayes model
nb_pred = nb.predict(x_test)

# Evaluate the accuracy and print the classification report for Naive Bayes model
nb_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, nb_pred)
print("Naive Bayes accuracy is %2.2f" % nb_accuracy)
print("Naive Bayes Classifier Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, nb_pred))

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Scale the data
scaler = StandardScaler()
x_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(x_train)
x_test_scaled = scaler.transform(x_test)

# k-Nearest Neighbors Classifier with parallel processing
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5, n_jobs=-1)
knn.fit(x_train_scaled, y_train)

# Predict using k-NN
knn_pred = knn.predict(x_test_scaled)

# Evaluate k-NN
knn_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, knn_pred)
print("k-Nearest Neighbors accuracy is %2.2f" % knn_accuracy)
print("k-Nearest Neighbors Classifier Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, knn_pred))

Next model which we applied is KNeighborsClassifier.

Accuracy is KNeighborsClassifier is 98% we also print classification report which include accuracy, precision, recall, f1-score Accuracy: matric to analyse classification model in machine learning. Number of correct predictions/ total predictions. Formula: TN+TP/TN+FP+TP+FN

Precision: ratio of correctly predict positive samples from total positive predict. Formula: TP/TP+FP

Recall: ratio of correctly positive prediction from all samples from actual sample. Formula: TP/TP+FN

F1 score: harmonic mean of the precision and recall of classification model. F1score=2 * recall * precision/recall + precision.

This all calculation calculated from ratio of true positive, true negative, false positive, false negative

True positive [TP]: actual value is true model also predict it true its true positive. True negative [TN]: actual value is false model predict it false its true negative. False positive [FP]: actual value is true model predict it true its false positive. False negative [FN]: actual value is false model predict it true its false negative.
